{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473407","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473407"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:07:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:07:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2404"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2404"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.76,0.05,0.01,0.1,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2404"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103567"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2404"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2404"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85984"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1967"},{"type":"tags","id":"2042"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"12916"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1698"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1705"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6183"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36765"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44073"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103567","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103567"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-week old newborn is brought to the hospital by her mother due to yellow discolouration in the infant\u0027s skin and eyes which has occurred gradually over the past two weeks. She is also worried that the girl\u2019s stools have become pale, white-coloured over the past five days. She thinks the infant\u0027s urine might be slightly darker in colour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe infant was breastfed naturally by her mother but had recently switched to milk formula intermittently as her mother has trouble expressing breast milk. The mother had a normal pregnancy without any complications during birth. The infant was born at 38 weeks gestation via vaginal delivery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears comfortable with vital signs within normal limits. There is obvious jaundice in her sclera and across her skin. She is at a 50th percentile for her height and weight, and she has been tracking well in her growth. The cardiorespiratory examination is unremarkable. Abdominal examination finds no tenderness or faecal mass. The liver is palpated 3 cm below the costal margin. The rest of her examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory tests showed the following:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood typing: Group B positive\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal bilirubin: 25 mg/dL (0.1 \u2013 1.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDirect bilirubin: 15 mg/dL (0.1 \u2013 0.3)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlkaline phosphatase: 2600 U/L (25 \u2013 100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlanine aminotransferase: 35 U/L (10 \u2013 40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAspartate aminotransferase: 38 U/L (12 \u2013 38)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGamma-glutamyl transferase: 180 U/L (5 \u2013 50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Biliary atresia","Physiological jaundice","ABO compatibility","Breast milk jaundice","Galactosaemia"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is a three-week-old newborn that presents with jaundice and pale stools. This suggests that there is a conjugation of bilirubin within the liver or bile ducts that are unable to be converted to urobilinogen and stercobilin in the large intestines. This gives the characteristic pale stools in direct bilirubinaemia, also seen in the blood laboratory test. The elevated ALP signifies a cholestatic picture, potentially post-hepatic in nature. An important, but uncommon condition to be considered that leads to obstructive jaundice in the neonate is biliary atresia. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiliary atresia \u003C/strong\u003Eoccurs in some 1 per 10,000-15,000 live births and is the obliteration of the extrahepatic biliary system, commonly the common bile duct. This leads to cholestasis and build-up of conjugated bilirubin in the liver, and eventually secondary biliary cirrhosis and portal hypertension. Symptoms do not occur spontaneously after birth as the bile produced in a newborn is minimal. Symptoms may typically appear within the first two months of life.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhysiological jaundice\u003C/strong\u003E is due to transient unconjugated hyperbilirubinaemia. The onset is usually from the 3rd \u2013 8th day of life.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EABO compatibility\u003C/strong\u003E presents as jaundice almost spontaneously within the first day after birth, with anaemia and transient hyperbilirubinaemia. In addition, this would not explain her raised ALP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGalactosaemia\u003C/strong\u003E presents within the first few days after breastmilk/ formula has been introduced. Symptoms include lethargy and hypotonia in addition to jaundice. The patient is asymptomatic within the first two weeks of life which suggest that her metabolism pathway of galactose is intact.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pale stools in the presence of jaundice suggests an obstructive aetiology."],"references":["Bates MD, Bucuvalas JC, Alonso MH, Ryckman FC. Biliary atresia: pathogenesis and treatment. Semin Liver Dis. 1998;18:281. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9773428/","Haber BA, Russo P. Biliary atresia. Gastroenterol Clin North Am. 2003;32:891. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/14562580/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85984"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2404"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85984"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-23T20:18:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-23T20:19:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2404"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103567"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the